community: a test for inclusivity -- tAge-friendly cities and communities: a manifesto for change -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the drive towards creating age-friendly cities grows, this important book provides a comprehensive survey of theories and policies aimed at improving the quality of life of older people living in urban areas. In this book, part of the Ageing in a Global Context series, leading international researchers critically assess the problems and the potential of designing age-friendly environments. The book considers the different ways in which cities are responding to population ageing, the different strategies for developing age-friendly communities, and the extent to which older people themselves can be involved in the co-production of age-friendly policies and practices. The book includes a manifesto for the age-friendly movement, focused around tackling social inequality and promoting community empowerment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aBuffel, Tine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuffel, Tine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCalasanti, Toni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCannon, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChau, Pui Hing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheung, Francis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDale, Meredith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDannefer, Dale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Witte, Nico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct